translation:
A goat to the herd,  
take the kid to the pen,  
make hay from there,  
I will give hay to the cow;  
the cow gives me milk,  
I give milk to the piglet,  
the piglet gives me a flank,  
I give the flank to the mother-in-law;  
the mother-in-law gives me cake,  
I give the cake to Kalev,  
Kalev gives me iron,  
I give the iron to the rack;  
the rack gives me gold,  
I give the gold to the oak;  
the oak gives me a leaf,  
I give the leaf to the lamb;  
the lamb gives me wool,  
I give the wool to Eerik;  
Eerik makes me a new hut.

Who adorns the alder forest?  
The schoolmaster adorns the alder forest;  
Whose meadows are lush?  
The grandfather's meadows are lush;  
Whose trees are red?  
Kristjan's trees are red;  
Whose yard is grassy?  
Toss's yard is grassy;  
Whose gates are brass?  
The blacksmith's gates are brass;  
Who has a hollow hill?  
At Kullamägi.

Let the brewers be healthy,
brewers, rock brewers,
makers of the vine of wrath.
Here is what was put together from six.
The first was water, which is liquid;
the second came strong and full;
the third - dear junipers;
the fourth - malt, which is sweet;
the fifth - sour hops,
the sixth - those hot stones,
then for the seventh yeast was added.
Thus the beer was made ready.

A little instrument, a little joy;  
Dear kannel, a little plaything;  
Without the instrument, no household;  
Without the kannel, no companion.  
The instrument walks to taverns’ paths,  
The kannel to beer houses.  
But it’s looking for vodka buyers,  
Calling out to vodka sellers.

The party is ending, the party is ending, little family elder;
Beer is finished, kvass is gone in the family room;
Beer is finished, yeast at the bottom –
The joyful party is over.

Empty, knows not from where I came:  
Am I from Finland, or am I from Soare?  
I was made by black grouse;  
Laid by black birds;  
Woven by old starlings.  
Laid beneath the earth;  
Woven beneath the garden.  
I am a man from Märjamaa;  
My horse in front from Harjumaa;  
Myself on top from Pärnumaa;  
With a whip from Põltsamaa;  
A wide lash from Läänemaa.  
Uncles did not take me as their own;  
Aunts did not pay attention;  
Not before I became older;  
I grew a bigger family;  
When I got a horse keeper;  
A bridle holder.  
I went to the Finnish bridge:  
The Finnish bridge is flexible;  
The foundation beams are loud;  
Hans’s hat makes noise.  
Then uncles took me as their own;  
Then aunts paid attention:  
Look, here rides a young man —  
Horse wearing pearls in front,  
A copper carriage behind;  
The axle drips with tin;  
The wheel clacks with coins;  
The spokes with pennies;  
The rims with rouble pieces.

