Then aunts paid attention:  
Look, here rides a young man —  
Horse wearing pearls in front,  
A copper carriage behind;  
The axle drips with tin;  
The wheel clacks with coins;  
The spokes with pennies;  
The rims with rouble pieces.

Hello father, hello mother,  
Hello master and mistress;  
Hello father-in-law, hello mother-in-law,  
Hello bride, my young maiden;  
Hello room with written box,  
Roof with written beams;  
Hello floor of paper,  
Hello courtyard of silver;  
Hello daughter with golden writing,  
Hello son with silver feet;  
Hello tin streets,  
Hello copper gates;  
Hello silver courtyard birds,  
Hello golden cuckoo cakes;  
Hello everyone throughout,  
All the household to the end.

Do not curse the maidens,
Swear on your pure soul;
Do not curse the maiden’s mother;
Swear on the old woman;
Who made a bride expensive,
A maiden for forty [units of currency]? -
Before, you got a wife without money:
You got a girl on the other side,
Now you cannot get a wife for money.
You get a girl from the other side;
A maiden’s hair costs a thousand,
A maiden’s braid costs a hundred,
Fifty for the linen necklace, - -

Nobody knows where I came from:  
Am I from Finland, or am I from Soare?  
I was made by black grouses;  
I was laid by black birds;  
Feathered by old hawks.  
I was laid under the Mulgimaa hills;  
Feathered under the garden.  
I am a man from Märjamaa;  
My horse is from Harjumaa;  
I myself am from Pärnumaa;  
Whipped with a switch from Põltsamaa;  
With a wide strike from Läänemaa.  
Uncles did not take me as their own;  
Aunts did not pay attention;  
Not until I became older;  
I grew into a grown man;  
When I got a horse to tend;  
And a halter to put on its head.  
I went onto the bridge to Finland:  
The Finnish bridge with flexible boards;  
The foundation beams creaked;  
Hansu’s hat rustled.  
Then uncles took me as their own;  
Then aunts took notice:  
Look, here rides a young man -  
A horse with bells in front,  
A brass carriage behind;  
Its axle drips with tin;  
The wheel clatters with money;  
The spokes clink with pennies;  
The rims ring out with ruble coins.

