The spokes clink with pennies;  
The rims ring out with ruble coins.

The power of toil, the power of labor;  
The power of sorrow, the power of tears;  
The power of austerity, the power of gloom.  
Oh, this dear power of Kapo!  
And this good power of Härvitada,  
Love Aruküla:  
There, thighs are beaten on the instrument,  
At the dance, stomped impatiently;  
Walls are struck with song!  
In austerity, beaten with a whip;  
With a slap, walls are struck.

There is a saber dog,  
without a master’s command,  
eats my fatty meat,  
sucks lard from the butt,  
from the sail eats soap fat,  
from the side gets chimney soot fat,  
from behind the hand gets rat fat,  
from the groin gets cake fat.

Mother Ella, dear granny!  
Heat the stove with kitchen wood;  
Honor the whip to Virve ella,  
I will take the whip to Virve;  
So the broom flies!  
Whip strikes on the back of the neck –  
Whack strikes on the neck;  
Blue marks on the back. – –  
Oh, poor Esna parish, –  
Among other parishes!  
In the middle of the district;  
Whip lashes heard from Laiuse;  
Whip lashes to Paide! – –  
Misery in Alutaguse! –  
Maid’s crying in the meadow;  
I cried before, I cried yesterday,  
Again I cry, today I cry. – –  
***  
Mill’s golden eyebrows have withered,  
The eyes have hardened and grown straight? –  
Into the harsh village;  
To the graveyard of Esna parish.
